<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>DIVISION.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD>EXAMPLE I.</HEAD>
<P>Divide 25 dollars 6 dimes and 2 cents equally among 6 per&s;ons.</P>
<P><GAP DESC="math"></P>
<P>In this example, I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> in 25.4 times 6 is 2<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; from 25 and 1 <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">, that is 1 dollar <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> 10 dimes, which b<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">g added to the 6 d<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="3 letters">s in the next row make 16; then the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ix's in 16, 2 times (<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 span">) 6 i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">
<PB N="272" REF="023387_0274_0FBF6528788A4DE0">
12, from 16, and their remains 4, which being reduced in your mind, make 40 cents: this together with the 2 cents in the next row, makes 42; then I &s;ay the &s;ix's in 42, 7 times; here the work is ended; and each per&s;on's &s;hare is four dollars, two dimes, and &s;even cents.</P>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="subsection">
<HEAD>EXAMPLE II.</HEAD>
<P>Divide 462 dollars, 7 dimes, and 5 cents, equally among 25 men.</P>
